   {:e #blake3 "d05b257de6629bd93df3fb2c99483fb62b44968fffade99293aa3afe528dc7ed" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-49772c4079d19b93; Session entity: :task/t-774f479b\nFRONTIER-STEER REVISION — THREE NESTED LEARNING LOOPS IN ONE TASK: The implementation has three phases that can ship incrementally. PHASE A (ship first, immediate value): Static acquisition function. frontier_recommendation computes explore/deepen/bridge from fixed-weight features (connectivity, variance, novelty). The weights are constants (like JOIN_THRESHOLD was). This replaces the formulaic steering question immediately. DOGFOOD-5 target: 8+/10. PHASE B (ship second, closes calibration loop): Record each frontier recommendation as a hypothesis in the ledger. Measure outcome on next observe. Compute prediction error. Adjust weights at harvest via gradient descent. Weights become policy datoms. This is CALIBRATABLE-PARAMS applied to the acquisition function. PHASE C (ship third, enables transfer): Calibrated acquisition weights in seed output. CRDT merge transfers weights across projects. New projects start with the weighted average of all prior projects' calibrated weights. This is meta-learning / MAML for epistemology. IMPLEMENTATION ORDER: Phase A is ~150 LOC, immediate DOGFOOD impact. Phase B is ~100 LOC, requires hypothesis ledger wiring. Phase C is ~50 LOC seed change. Total: ~300 LOC across 3 incrementally shippable phases.; THE SELF-IMPROVING ACQUISITION FUNCTION: FRONTIER-STEER should not just compute recommendations — it should LEARN from outcomes. Every frontier recommendation is a PREDICTION ('I predict observing materialize/ will yield high information gain'). The next observation IS the outcome (did it produce high surprise? bridge concepts? change F(S)?). The hypothesis ledger already records predictions vs outcomes. Wire frontier recommendations into it: (1) At recommend time: record hypothesis { predicted: 'explore materialize/ yields gain=0.7', boundary: 'coverage', confidence: gain_score }. (2) At next observe time: measure actual gain = surprise of new observation + concept_bridges_formed + delta_F(S). Record as outcome. (3) At harvest time: calibration step adjusts the acquisition weights (connectivity_weight, variance_weight, novelty_weight) via gradient descent on prediction error. (4) Calibrated weights are stored as policy datoms. Transfer via CRDT merge — a team that learned 'connectivity matters more than variance for Go projects' shares it with every Go team. THIS IS THE COMPLETE LEARNING SYSTEM. Three nested loops: (A) OBSERVE loop: single-observation concept assignment + centroid update (SGD). (B) HARVEST loop: crystallization + acquisition weight calibration (batch). (C) CROSS-SESSION loop: calibrated weights in seed + CRDT merge (transfer learning). Each loop operates at a different timescale and optimizes a different level: observations optimize beliefs, harvests optimize ontology, cross-session optimizes the learning algorithm itself. This is the meta-learning architecture — MAML for epistemology." :op :assert}
